WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:15.000
The Lost Treasure of Bodega Bay

00:15.000 --> 00:18.000
by Gina D. V. Clement

00:18.000 --> 00:21.000
copyright, black cat publishing.

00:31.000 --> 00:34.000
Introduction

00:34.000 --> 00:39.000
This story takes place in San Francisco and in Bodega Bay.

00:39.000 --> 00:45.000
San Francisco is a beautiful city on the Pacific coast in the state of California.

00:45.000 --> 00:51.000
Bodega Bay is a small town on the coast, north of San Francisco.

00:51.000 --> 00:59.000
The story talks about a big marine sanctuary called the Gulf of the Farrelones National Marine Sanctuary.

00:59.000 --> 01:08.000
27 miles west of San Francisco and the Point Reyes National Seashore, which is another protected area.

01:08.000 --> 01:10.000
San Francisco

01:10.000 --> 01:15.000
San Francisco is one of America's most beautiful and exciting cities.

01:15.000 --> 01:21.000
It is an international center for business, education, science, and the arts.

01:21.000 --> 01:24.000
The city is famous for its hills.

01:24.000 --> 01:30.000
It was built on 43 hills and you can always get great views of the bay.

01:30.000 --> 01:38.000
The main tourist attractions are the Golden Gate Bridge, Alcatraz Island, Telegraph Hill, and Fisherman's Wharf.

01:38.000 --> 01:43.000
Around 800,000 people live in the city today.

01:43.000 --> 01:49.000
The Farrelones National Marine Sanctuary and Point Reyes

01:49.000 --> 01:57.000
The Farrelones National Marine Sanctuary is one of the 13 marine sanctuaries in the United States.

01:57.000 --> 02:06.000
There are seven groups of islands and it is home to whales, dolphins, great white sharks, sea lions, and seabirds.

02:06.000 --> 02:11.000
Tourists can't go onto the islands, but they can see them from boats.

02:11.000 --> 02:15.000
Only scientists can go on the islands.

02:15.000 --> 02:21.000
Point Reyes National Seashore is part of the Farrelones National Marine Sanctuary.

02:21.000 --> 02:28.000
It was set up in 1962 to protect all kinds of sea life, plants, and trees.

02:28.000 --> 02:36.000
Visitors can walk along the Long Beach and watch whales and dolphins swim by.

02:36.000 --> 02:45.000
Bodega Bay Bodega Bay is a small town on the Pacific coast, about 40 miles northwest of San Francisco.

02:45.000 --> 02:54.000
The bay was discovered in 1775 by Peruvian explorer Juan Francisco de la Bodega Ichodra.

02:54.000 --> 02:58.000
About 2,000 people live there today.

02:58.000 --> 03:04.000
The town was the setting for Alfred Hitchcock's film The Birds in 1963.

03:04.000 --> 03:12.000
It is well known for its long sandy beaches and its protected harbor.

03:12.000 --> 03:18.000
Chapter 1 The Story of the Ghost Ship

03:18.000 --> 03:24.000
Kate and Mike Sullivan live in San Francisco with their parents and their pet dog Lucky.

03:24.000 --> 03:33.000
Their home is on Russian Hill, and from their house Kate and Mike have a great view of San Francisco Bay and the Golden Gate Bridge.

03:33.000 --> 03:41.000
Their father, Frank Sullivan, is a professor and teaches marine biology at San Francisco University.

03:41.000 --> 03:47.000
Their mother, Liz Sullivan, works in a big bookshop in the city center.

03:47.000 --> 03:51.000
Kate is 14 and her brother Mike is 15.

03:51.000 --> 03:58.000
Kate goes to Lincoln Middle School and Mike goes to Galileo High School.

03:58.000 --> 04:03.000
Kate is a pretty girl with long blonde hair and blue eyes.

04:03.000 --> 04:06.000
She likes school but doesn't like math.

04:06.000 --> 04:10.000
She loves dancing and belongs to the Lincoln Dance Club.

04:10.000 --> 04:16.000
She's a very good dancer and wants to become a professional dancer one day.

04:16.000 --> 04:20.000
Mike is tall with brown hair and blue eyes.

04:20.000 --> 04:25.000
He is in his first year of high school and he always has a lot of homework.

04:25.000 --> 04:32.000
He is an excellent swimmer and is a member of the Galileo High School swimming team.

04:32.000 --> 04:37.000
Our story begins on a sunny Monday morning early in June.

04:37.000 --> 04:39.000
Half past seven.

04:39.000 --> 04:41.000
Said Kate, putting on her watch.

04:41.000 --> 04:43.000
Time for breakfast.

04:43.000 --> 04:45.000
Two more weeks and school is over.

04:45.000 --> 04:47.000
Said Mike, happily.

04:47.000 --> 04:51.000
Summer vacation, the best time of the year.

04:51.000 --> 04:53.000
Said Kate, laughing.

04:53.000 --> 04:59.000
Kate was also excited because after the summer she was going to start high school.

04:59.000 --> 05:00.000
Good morning.

05:00.000 --> 05:03.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan, who was preparing breakfast.

05:03.000 --> 05:09.000
Kate, remember you have an eye doctor's appointment today after school with Dr. Lee.

05:09.000 --> 05:10.000
Please don't be late.

05:10.000 --> 05:12.000
I know mom.

05:12.000 --> 05:13.000
Said Kate.

05:13.000 --> 05:17.000
But I don't want to go. I don't want to wear glasses.

05:17.000 --> 05:22.000
Kate, you can't study well at school. You need a pair of glasses.

05:22.000 --> 05:26.000
If you don't get them, your eyesight will get worse.

05:26.000 --> 05:29.000
Said Mr. Sullivan, drinking a cup of coffee.

05:29.000 --> 05:34.000
There's nothing wrong with glasses. I wear them. A lot of kids wear them.

05:34.000 --> 05:37.000
Susan Garcia in my class just got glasses.

05:37.000 --> 05:38.000
Said Mike.

05:38.000 --> 05:42.000
And she looks better with glasses than without them.

05:42.000 --> 05:46.000
Kate, slowly ate her breakfast and said.

05:46.000 --> 05:50.000
Okay, okay. I'll wear them to see the board.

05:50.000 --> 05:53.000
Suddenly there was a knock on the door.

05:53.000 --> 05:56.000
It was Julie Bennett, Kate's best friend.

05:56.000 --> 05:57.000
Hi.

05:57.000 --> 06:02.000
Said Julie, a pretty 14-year-old girl with short black hair.

06:02.000 --> 06:05.000
I came to pick you up so we can walk to school together.

06:05.000 --> 06:06.000
Hi, Julie.

06:06.000 --> 06:07.000
Said Kate.

06:07.000 --> 06:11.000
I'm still having breakfast. Just sit down and have some cookies.

06:11.000 --> 06:13.000
Hi, Julie.

06:13.000 --> 06:19.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan as she turned on the television to watch the weather report and the morning news.

06:19.000 --> 06:23.000
Another warm sunny day in San Francisco.

06:23.000 --> 06:24.000
Said the speaker.

06:24.000 --> 06:30.000
With heavy afternoon fog along the Pacific coast, particularly in the Bodega Bay area.

06:30.000 --> 06:33.000
It's always foggy in Bodega Bay.

06:33.000 --> 06:35.000
Said Mike.

06:35.000 --> 06:37.000
Do you remember our adventure up there?

06:37.000 --> 06:40.000
When did you go to Bodega Bay?

06:40.000 --> 06:42.000
asked Julie, eating a cookie.

06:42.000 --> 06:45.000
It was about 18 months ago.

06:45.000 --> 06:46.000
Said Kate.

06:46.000 --> 06:50.000
And Carlos Gomez came with us. We had quite an adventure.

06:50.000 --> 06:52.000
Sounds exciting.

06:52.000 --> 06:53.000
Said Julie.

06:53.000 --> 06:55.000
Tell me about it.

06:55.000 --> 07:00.000
Kate looked at Mike and her parents, and they all started laughing.

07:00.000 --> 07:04.000
Well, Mom and I have to go to work.

07:04.000 --> 07:05.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

07:05.000 --> 07:09.000
It's getting late. See you this evening. Bye.

07:09.000 --> 07:11.000
Okay, let me tell you about it.

07:11.000 --> 07:14.000
Said Kate, looking at her watch.

07:14.000 --> 07:21.000
Mom, Dad, Mike, Carlos and I went to the Farallon Islands on Dad's new boat, the Pelican.

07:21.000 --> 07:24.000
He was studying the sea birds and the fish in the area.

07:24.000 --> 07:30.000
We were all excited about the trip, but the first night I saw the ghost of a boy near my bed.

07:30.000 --> 07:34.000
I screamed and was scared, but no one believed me.

07:34.000 --> 07:40.000
Then one night, Mom and Dad heard a ship's bell and saw a yellow light at sea.

07:40.000 --> 07:45.000
They thought someone needed help, so they took the lifeboat and left the Pelican.

07:45.000 --> 07:49.000
The next morning, we couldn't find them, and we were worried.

07:49.000 --> 07:52.000
We took the boat and went to look for them.

07:52.000 --> 07:57.000
In the fog, we saw a strange old ship, the Sonora.

07:57.000 --> 08:04.000
Later, we discovered that it was an old Spanish pirate ship that was lost at sea in 1608.

08:04.000 --> 08:08.000
What? A ship that was lost 400 years ago?

08:08.000 --> 08:11.000
Cried Julie, who stopped eating.

08:11.000 --> 08:13.000
Yes, it was a ghost ship.

08:13.000 --> 08:15.000
Said Kate.

08:15.000 --> 08:19.000
We knew Mom and Dad were on that ship because their lifeboat was there.

08:19.000 --> 08:25.000
We were scared, but we went onto the ship and we had a terrible surprise.

08:25.000 --> 08:28.000
The ship's crew were all ghosts.

08:28.000 --> 08:30.000
Ghosts of sailors and pirates.

08:30.000 --> 08:35.000
We were terrified because we saw Mom and Dad sitting in a corner.

08:35.000 --> 08:40.000
We went to help them, but then the ghost of Captain Salamanca spoke to us.

08:40.000 --> 08:46.000
He was terrible. He killed people and they became part of his crew of ghosts.

08:46.000 --> 08:52.000
He said he needed a big crew because he was looking for some lost treasure.

08:52.000 --> 08:54.000
He wanted to kill us all.

08:54.000 --> 09:00.000
Suddenly, Lucky jumped on the table and a big candle fell and a fire started.

09:00.000 --> 09:06.000
Ghosts are afraid of fire, so they moved away and we helped Mom and Dad get off the ship.

09:06.000 --> 09:12.000
Before leaving, Mike saw Captain Salamanca's treasure map on the table and took it.

09:12.000 --> 09:14.000
What an adventure!

09:14.000 --> 09:16.000
Said Julie.

09:16.000 --> 09:18.000
Do you still have the treasure map?

09:18.000 --> 09:20.000
Mike has it.

09:20.000 --> 09:21.000
Said Kate.

09:21.000 --> 09:24.000
Buddy hit it because it's a big secret.

09:24.000 --> 09:28.000
That afternoon, Kate went to the eye doctor with Julie.

09:28.000 --> 09:31.000
Dr. Lee was a friendly young man.

09:31.000 --> 09:34.000
He gave her an eye test and said,

09:34.000 --> 09:38.000
Kate, you need glasses to see things in the distance.

09:38.000 --> 09:44.000
Julie helped Kate choose her new glasses and she gave them to Dr. Lee, who said,

09:44.000 --> 09:49.000
Good choice. They'll be ready on Thursday, Kate.

09:52.000 --> 09:55.000
Chapter 2. A new adventure.

09:56.000 --> 10:02.000
Friday was a big day for Kate because she wore her new glasses to school for the first time.

10:02.000 --> 10:07.000
When she walked into the classroom, everyone turned around and looked at her.

10:07.000 --> 10:09.000
Wow!

10:09.000 --> 10:12.000
They said, new glasses!

10:12.000 --> 10:17.000
Kate's heart was beating fast and her hands felt cold.

10:17.000 --> 10:20.000
She walked to her desk and sat down.

10:21.000 --> 10:22.000
Hi, Kate.

10:22.000 --> 10:23.000
Said Tom.

10:23.000 --> 10:25.000
The boy she liked.

10:25.000 --> 10:26.000
New glasses.

10:26.000 --> 10:28.000
You look great.

10:28.000 --> 10:29.000
Thanks, Tom.

10:29.000 --> 10:30.000
Said Kate.

10:30.000 --> 10:32.000
Turning red with embarrassment.

10:32.000 --> 10:35.000
His opinion was very important to her.

10:35.000 --> 10:38.000
I really like your new glasses.

10:38.000 --> 10:41.000
Said her friend, Kelly.

10:41.000 --> 10:45.000
Kate suddenly felt happy and was ready for the lesson.

10:45.000 --> 10:47.000
A math test.

10:47.000 --> 10:54.000
That evening at the dinner table, the Sullivan family was having a noisy conversation because everyone had something to say.

10:54.000 --> 10:57.000
Well, how was your day at school, Kate?

10:57.000 --> 10:58.000
Asked her mother.

10:58.000 --> 11:00.000
Oh, just great, Mom.

11:00.000 --> 11:02.000
Said Kate, smiling.

11:02.000 --> 11:04.000
Everyone liked my new glasses.

11:04.000 --> 11:05.000
Even Tom.

11:05.000 --> 11:08.000
And the math test was okay, I think.

11:08.000 --> 11:10.000
And how was your day, Mike?

11:10.000 --> 11:11.000
Asked his father.

11:11.000 --> 11:12.000
Exciting.

11:12.000 --> 11:14.000
Mike said.

11:14.000 --> 11:15.000
Guess what?

11:16.000 --> 11:20.000
Our science class is going to Muir Woods National Park next week.

11:20.000 --> 11:25.000
It's part of a class project on trees, forests, and conservation.

11:25.000 --> 11:30.000
We're leaving early on Tuesday morning and coming back before dinner time.

11:30.000 --> 11:31.000
Muir Woods.

11:31.000 --> 11:33.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

11:33.000 --> 11:36.000
It's one of the most beautiful forests in the world.

11:36.000 --> 11:38.000
Sounds like fun.

11:38.000 --> 11:39.000
Said Kate.

11:39.000 --> 11:44.000
Well, this evening I have some exciting news, too.

11:44.000 --> 11:46.000
Mr. Sullivan.

11:46.000 --> 11:48.000
Everyone at the table looked at him.

11:48.000 --> 11:51.000
He usually didn't have anything exciting to say.

11:51.000 --> 11:53.000
What is it, Frank?

11:53.000 --> 11:54.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

11:54.000 --> 11:56.000
Who wanted to know the news?

11:56.000 --> 12:02.000
Next week, I'm going to the Monterey Bay Aquarium to talk to Professor Simpson.

12:02.000 --> 12:03.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

12:03.000 --> 12:10.000
The aquarium is doing an important study on sea life in the Pacific Ocean, particularly on the Great White Shark.

12:10.000 --> 12:16.000
They want me to spend some time at the Farallon Islands and the Point Reyes National Seashore.

12:16.000 --> 12:19.000
Another trip to the Farallon Islands.

12:19.000 --> 12:21.000
Said his wife, smiling.

12:21.000 --> 12:22.000
Wow, Dad.

12:22.000 --> 12:27.000
Do you mean you're going to the Farallons and Point Reyes on the Pelican?

12:27.000 --> 12:29.000
Asked Mike, looking at Kate.

12:29.000 --> 12:31.000
Yes, that's right.

12:31.000 --> 12:33.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

12:33.000 --> 12:37.000
I'll probably stay about a week and more the Pelican in the harbor at Bodega Bay.

12:37.000 --> 12:39.000
When are you going?

12:39.000 --> 12:41.000
Asked Kate excitedly.

12:41.000 --> 12:44.000
At the end of June or the beginning of July.

12:44.000 --> 12:45.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

12:45.000 --> 12:47.000
Can we come along?

12:47.000 --> 12:49.000
Cried Kate and Mike.

12:49.000 --> 12:50.000
Of course!

12:50.000 --> 12:52.000
Said Mr. Sullivan laughing.

12:52.000 --> 12:54.000
What about Lucky?

12:54.000 --> 12:55.000
Asked Kate.

12:56.000 --> 12:59.000
Lucky heard his name and started barking.

13:00.000 --> 13:02.000
Yes, Lucky can come too.

13:02.000 --> 13:04.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

13:04.000 --> 13:07.000
It'll be great fun like last time.

13:07.000 --> 13:08.000
Said Mike.

13:08.000 --> 13:10.000
But without the ghosts.

13:10.000 --> 13:11.000
Said Kate nervously.

13:11.000 --> 13:15.000
Yes, without the ghosts and the ghost ship.

13:15.000 --> 13:17.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

13:17.000 --> 13:20.000
Who still remembered that terrible adventure?

13:20.000 --> 13:21.000
Oh, Dad.

13:21.000 --> 13:24.000
Can we invite Carlos like last time?

13:24.000 --> 13:26.000
Asked Mike.

13:26.000 --> 13:29.000
Carlos Gomez was Mike's best friend.

13:29.000 --> 13:34.000
He was Hispano American and he spoke Spanish and English perfectly.

13:34.000 --> 13:39.000
He was a tall, friendly boy with short black hair and dark eyes.

13:39.000 --> 13:41.000
And he lived near the Sullivan's.

13:41.000 --> 13:42.000
Why not?

13:42.000 --> 13:45.000
Said Mr. Sullivan, smiling at his son.

13:45.000 --> 13:46.000
Thanks, Dad.

13:46.000 --> 13:47.000
Cried Mike.

13:47.000 --> 13:50.000
Who started making secret plans.

13:50.000 --> 13:54.000
Kate and Mike helped their parents clean up after dinner.

13:54.000 --> 13:57.000
Then they went up to Mike's bedroom.

13:57.000 --> 14:01.000
Mike closed the door and Kate put on some music.

14:01.000 --> 14:03.000
What do you think of the news?

14:03.000 --> 14:04.000
Ask Mike.

14:04.000 --> 14:06.000
I can hardly believe it.

14:06.000 --> 14:07.000
Said Kate.

14:07.000 --> 14:10.000
Where did you put Captain Salamanca's old treasure map?

14:10.000 --> 14:12.000
It's in a safe place.

14:12.000 --> 14:13.000
Said Mike.

14:13.000 --> 14:16.000
Looking at the big bookshelf on the wall.

14:16.000 --> 14:20.000
Now we can study the map and start looking for the treasure.

14:20.000 --> 14:24.000
Dad will be busy with his work and Mom always helps him.

14:24.000 --> 14:25.000
We'll be free.

14:25.000 --> 14:28.000
This is going to be a great summer.

14:28.000 --> 14:29.000
Said Kate.

14:29.000 --> 14:31.000
Wait until I tell Carlos.

14:31.000 --> 14:33.000
Said Mike, picking up his cell phone.

14:33.000 --> 14:34.000
Yeah.

14:34.000 --> 14:35.000
Said Kate.

14:35.000 --> 14:37.000
And he can help us understand the map.

14:37.000 --> 14:40.000
The words are written in Spanish.

14:43.000 --> 14:45.000
Sharks.

14:45.000 --> 14:48.000
A shark is a kind of fish.

14:48.000 --> 14:52.000
There are about 400 different kinds of sharks.

14:52.000 --> 14:57.000
Sharks live in different parts of the world in the warm seas of the south

14:57.000 --> 15:00.000
and in the cold waters of the north.

15:00.000 --> 15:05.000
Some live at the bottom of the sea and others swim near the coast.

15:05.000 --> 15:11.000
Sharks swam in the sea before dinosaurs walked on the earth.

15:11.000 --> 15:15.000
A lot of sharks are gray and have long bodies.

15:15.000 --> 15:18.000
But some sharks have different shapes.

15:18.000 --> 15:23.000
For example, hammerhead sharks have big, flat heads.

15:23.000 --> 15:28.000
Angel sharks live on the bottom of the sea and have flat bodies.

15:28.000 --> 15:32.000
Most sharks are between 60 and 90 centimeters long.

15:32.000 --> 15:37.000
The biggest shark is the whale shark, and it is longer than a bus.

15:37.000 --> 15:43.000
The smallest is the pygmy shark, and it is about the size of a banana.

15:43.000 --> 15:48.000
Most sharks have a lot of very strong teeth that look like triangles.

15:48.000 --> 15:52.000
When a shark loses a tooth, another grows in its place.

15:52.000 --> 15:57.000
Sharks usually hunt alone, but sometimes they hunt in groups.

15:57.000 --> 16:00.000
Sharks are very good hunters.

16:00.000 --> 16:05.000
They can feel the movements of other animals near to them, and they can see well.

16:05.000 --> 16:11.000
Sharks can hear sounds from far away, like the sound of a boat or a ship.

16:11.000 --> 16:15.000
Sharks also have an excellent sense of smell.

16:15.000 --> 16:19.000
Most people think all sharks are dangerous, but some of the biggest sharks

16:19.000 --> 16:24.000
eat only very small plants and animals in the sea called plankton.

16:24.000 --> 16:28.000
One of the most dangerous sharks is the Great White.

16:28.000 --> 16:35.000
It usually attacks and kills seals, dolphins, other sharks, and sometimes people.

16:35.000 --> 16:38.000
The Great White Shark.

16:38.000 --> 16:45.000
The Great White Shark is about six meters long and weighs about 2,000 kilograms.

16:45.000 --> 16:49.000
It can live from 30 to 100 years.

16:50.000 --> 16:57.000
In Steven Spielberg's 1975 film Jaws, the Great White Shark is a terrible man-eater.

16:57.000 --> 17:00.000
But Great White Sharks don't usually eat people.

17:00.000 --> 17:06.000
They often think a person in the sea is a seal and attack it by mistake.

17:06.000 --> 17:09.000
Sometimes Great White Sharks attack boats.

17:09.000 --> 17:16.000
They are always very hungry, and sometimes they even eat objects like tins and bottles.

17:16.000 --> 17:19.000
Sharks in danger.

17:19.000 --> 17:22.000
Today, sharks are in danger.

17:22.000 --> 17:28.000
People kill them for sport, food, and sometimes by mistake.

17:28.000 --> 17:34.000
Soup, made from shark fins, is a popular dish in some parts of the world.

17:34.000 --> 17:39.000
Sometimes, fishermen catch sharks and cut off their fins.

17:39.000 --> 17:42.000
Then they throw the sharks back into the sea.

17:42.000 --> 17:46.000
Without their fins, sharks cannot swim, and they die.

17:46.000 --> 17:55.000
Every year, more than 100 million sharks are killed, and some kinds of sharks are in danger of extinction.

17:59.000 --> 18:02.000
Chapter 3. The Treasure Map

18:02.000 --> 18:07.000
Mike's science class had a great time at Muir Woods National Park.

18:07.000 --> 18:13.000
Miss Williamson, the science teacher, showed them some of the world's oldest and tallest trees.

18:13.000 --> 18:20.000
She was everyone's favorite teacher at Galileo High because her classes were always interesting and fun.

18:20.000 --> 18:26.000
She started the Galileo Science Club, and Mike and Carlos were both members.

18:26.000 --> 18:31.000
There were club meetings every Wednesday afternoon after school.

18:32.000 --> 18:39.000
When Mike and Carlos came back from Muir Woods, they went to Carlos's house to talk about their summer trip.

18:39.000 --> 18:41.000
I'm really excited about this trip.

18:41.000 --> 18:43.000
Said Carlos.

18:43.000 --> 18:46.000
With the old pirate map, we can look for the treasure.

18:46.000 --> 18:48.000
And if we're lucky, we'll find it.

18:48.000 --> 18:49.000
Said Mike.

18:49.000 --> 18:51.000
It won't be easy.

18:51.000 --> 18:52.000
Said Carlos.

18:52.000 --> 18:57.000
Pirates were clever people, and their maps had secret messages that are difficult to understand.

18:57.000 --> 18:59.000
Do you have the map with you?

18:59.000 --> 19:02.000
No, I hit it on the bookshelf in my room.

19:02.000 --> 19:03.000
Said Mike.

19:03.000 --> 19:05.000
Only Kate knows where it is.

19:05.000 --> 19:07.000
Do your parents know about it?

19:07.000 --> 19:08.000
Asked Carlos.

19:08.000 --> 19:10.000
No, not yet.

19:10.000 --> 19:11.000
Said Mike.

19:11.000 --> 19:15.000
My mom always says, be careful, it's dangerous.

19:15.000 --> 19:18.000
They laughed, and Carlos said.

19:18.000 --> 19:20.000
My parents are the same.

19:20.000 --> 19:23.000
Everything that's fun is dangerous.

19:23.000 --> 19:25.000
But we'll be careful.

19:25.000 --> 19:26.000
Said Mike.

19:27.000 --> 19:31.000
Next time, let's meet at your house, and we can look at the map.

19:31.000 --> 19:32.000
Said Carlos.

19:32.000 --> 19:33.000
Good idea.

19:33.000 --> 19:34.000
Said Mike.

19:34.000 --> 19:36.000
It's all written in Spanish.

19:36.000 --> 19:38.000
No problem for me.

19:38.000 --> 19:41.000
Said Carlos, laughing.

19:41.000 --> 19:47.000
Friday was the last day of school, and everyone talked about their exciting vacation plans.

19:47.000 --> 19:53.000
That evening, Mr. Sullivan told his family more about the trip, and Mike and Kate listened carefully.

19:53.000 --> 20:00.000
We'll sail next Wednesday from Marina Harbor, and go north to Bodega Bay, where we'll

20:00.000 --> 20:02.000
more the Pelican.

20:02.000 --> 20:05.000
We'll probably stay five or six days.

20:05.000 --> 20:12.000
I have to work at Point Reyes National Seashore and the Farallon Islands, and mom is going to help me.

20:12.000 --> 20:14.000
Now, will you three be okay?

20:14.000 --> 20:17.000
Do you have something to do, or will you get bored?

20:17.000 --> 20:20.000
Oh, we won't get bored, Dad.

20:20.000 --> 20:23.000
Said Kate, thinking about the treasure map.

20:23.000 --> 20:24.000
Don't worry, Dad.

20:24.000 --> 20:25.000
Said Mike.

20:25.000 --> 20:31.000
Kate, Carlos and I can stay on the beach, play in the sea, or go for walks in the hills.

20:31.000 --> 20:32.000
Alright.

20:32.000 --> 20:34.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

20:34.000 --> 20:37.000
You can stay on the beach, but you mustn't swim in the sea.

20:37.000 --> 20:43.000
Remember, this is the Pacific Ocean, and there are a lot of sharks, and they swim close to the beach.

20:43.000 --> 20:45.000
They're very dangerous.

20:45.000 --> 20:47.000
Mike laughed and said,

20:47.000 --> 20:49.000
We'll be careful, Mom.

20:49.000 --> 20:51.000
And we won't go swimming.

20:51.000 --> 20:54.000
You're free to do what you want during the day.

20:54.000 --> 20:56.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

20:56.000 --> 21:00.000
But we'll meet for dinner on the Pelican every evening at about six.

21:00.000 --> 21:06.000
If you have any problems, just call or text Mom or me on our cell phones.

21:06.000 --> 21:10.000
Kate and Mike went upstairs and phoned Carlos.

21:10.000 --> 21:11.000
Hi, Carlos.

21:11.000 --> 21:12.000
Said Mike.

21:12.000 --> 21:14.000
Can you come to my house right now?

21:14.000 --> 21:17.000
We can look at the map and start making plans.

21:17.000 --> 21:19.000
I'll be there in ten minutes.

21:19.000 --> 21:21.000
Said Carlos, happily.

21:21.000 --> 21:26.000
Mike took the old treasure map from the bookshelf and put it on his desk.

21:26.000 --> 21:31.000
When Carlos arrived, the three of them sat around the desk and looked at it carefully.

21:31.000 --> 21:34.000
Gee, this is exciting.

21:34.000 --> 21:36.000
Said Carlos, touching it.

21:36.000 --> 21:38.000
An old pirate map.

21:38.000 --> 21:43.000
Look, that's where Bodega Bay is, but it doesn't say that.

21:43.000 --> 21:45.000
It just says Bahia.

21:45.000 --> 21:50.000
That's interesting because today in Spanish, Bay is Bahia.

21:50.000 --> 21:54.000
But maybe the spelling was different in the 1600s.

21:54.000 --> 21:59.000
Looking at this map, we can see a town already existed there at that time.

21:59.000 --> 22:01.000
It was probably a pirate's town.

22:01.000 --> 22:03.000
Said Mike.

22:03.000 --> 22:07.000
There's a big harbor, the perfect place for pirates to hide.

22:07.000 --> 22:12.000
This is also very interesting because my book on the history of California,

22:12.000 --> 22:18.000
says that Bodega Bay wasn't discovered until 1775.

22:18.000 --> 22:23.000
Looking at this map, people lived in the area long before.

22:23.000 --> 22:25.000
Look on the corner of the map.

22:25.000 --> 22:26.000
Said Kate.

22:26.000 --> 22:29.000
There's a date, 1608.

22:29.000 --> 22:32.000
That's the year of the shipwreck of the Sonora.

22:32.000 --> 22:33.000
Said Carlos.

22:33.000 --> 22:39.000
Captain Salamanca probably hit his treasure that year before the shipwreck in November.

22:39.000 --> 22:40.000
Hmm.

22:40.000 --> 22:43.000
But what else does it say on his map?

22:43.000 --> 22:45.000
Asked Mike.

22:45.000 --> 22:49.000
Hmm, north of the town, there's the word Cementario.

22:49.000 --> 22:51.000
In Spanish, that means cemetery.

22:51.000 --> 22:53.000
Said Carlos.

22:53.000 --> 22:55.000
It was probably the town cemetery.

22:55.000 --> 23:01.000
Near the cemetery, there's a place called Hacienda Estrada.

23:01.000 --> 23:02.000
Said Mike.

23:02.000 --> 23:07.000
And there's a small river near it called Rio Estrada.

23:07.000 --> 23:10.000
Hacienda means a big farm or ranch.

23:10.000 --> 23:13.000
And Estrada was probably the name of the family who owned it.

23:13.000 --> 23:14.000
Said Carlos.

23:14.000 --> 23:18.000
Look, there's a drawing of a lighthouse on the coast.

23:18.000 --> 23:19.000
Said Mike.

23:19.000 --> 23:24.000
There's a big black X east of the town with the word Agua.

23:24.000 --> 23:25.000
Said Kate.

23:25.000 --> 23:27.000
Agua in Spanish means water.

23:27.000 --> 23:28.000
Said Carlos.

23:28.000 --> 23:31.000
That was probably where the pirates got their drinking water.

23:31.000 --> 23:33.000
A water well.

23:33.000 --> 23:39.000
There's some red lines that go south from the town to what is now Doren Beach.

23:39.000 --> 23:40.000
Said Mike.

23:40.000 --> 23:42.000
But where's the treasure?

23:42.000 --> 23:43.000
Asked Kate.

23:43.000 --> 23:45.000
Good question.

23:45.000 --> 23:46.000
Said Mike.

23:46.000 --> 23:50.000
The places on the map are probably important clues.

23:50.000 --> 23:52.000
We have almost a week to explore them.

23:52.000 --> 23:53.000
Said Carlos.

23:53.000 --> 23:56.000
Why don't we start with the water well?

23:56.000 --> 23:57.000
Said Kate excitedly.

23:57.000 --> 23:59.000
That's a good place to hide a treasure.

23:59.000 --> 24:00.000
Okay.

24:00.000 --> 24:02.000
Said Mike and Carlos.

24:02.000 --> 24:05.000
That'll be the first place we look.

24:05.000 --> 24:10.000
Said Mike.

24:10.000 --> 24:11.000
Chapter four.

24:11.000 --> 24:14.000
The treasure chest.

24:14.000 --> 24:20.000
The pelican left Marina Harbor in San Francisco on a foggy Wednesday morning.

24:20.000 --> 24:28.000
Early in the afternoon, the Sullivan's and Carlos got to the town of Bodega Bay and moored the boat at the small pier.

24:28.000 --> 24:29.000
They had lunch.

24:29.000 --> 24:31.000
And then Mr. Sullivan said.

24:31.000 --> 24:35.000
Your mom and I have to start working and we're sailing to Point Reyes.

24:35.000 --> 24:37.000
We'll be back at the pier at dinner time.

24:37.000 --> 24:38.000
Have fun.

24:38.000 --> 24:39.000
Thanks.

24:39.000 --> 24:41.000
Said the three friends.

24:41.000 --> 24:42.000
See you at dinner.

24:42.000 --> 24:46.000
They got off the pelican and watched it sail away.

24:46.000 --> 24:47.000
Do you have the map?

24:47.000 --> 24:48.000
Asked Carlos.

24:48.000 --> 24:49.000
Yeah.

24:49.000 --> 24:50.000
It's in my bag.

24:50.000 --> 24:52.000
Said Mike, looking at his watch.

24:52.000 --> 24:54.000
It's half past two.

24:54.000 --> 24:57.000
We have about four hours before dinner time.

24:57.000 --> 24:59.000
This is exciting.

24:59.000 --> 25:00.000
Said Kate.

25:00.000 --> 25:02.000
We can start on our treasure hunt.

25:02.000 --> 25:05.000
Mike took the map out and said.

25:05.000 --> 25:08.000
Let's start with the water well.

25:08.000 --> 25:11.000
The three friends looked at the map carefully.

25:11.000 --> 25:14.000
The water well is east of the town.

25:14.000 --> 25:15.000
Said Carlos.

25:15.000 --> 25:19.000
The harbor is west of the town and the hills are east.

25:19.000 --> 25:21.000
We have to go to the hills.

25:21.000 --> 25:24.000
They looked east and saw some brown hills.

25:24.000 --> 25:26.000
Let's explore them.

25:26.000 --> 25:27.000
Said Mike.

25:27.000 --> 25:29.000
And see if the water well is still there.

25:29.000 --> 25:32.000
We can follow this path.

25:32.000 --> 25:37.000
They followed the path into the hills and spent the afternoon looking for the water well.

25:37.000 --> 25:39.000
But they found nothing.

25:39.000 --> 25:42.000
Lucky had a lot of fun running up and down the hills.

25:42.000 --> 25:45.000
And everyone enjoyed watching him.

25:45.000 --> 25:48.000
I don't think there's a water well in these hills.

25:48.000 --> 25:51.000
Said Kate, who was hot and tired.

25:51.000 --> 25:53.000
And I'm thirsty.

25:53.000 --> 25:55.000
There's nothing in these hills.

25:55.000 --> 25:57.000
Said Carlos laughing.

25:57.000 --> 26:00.000
Hey guys, it's almost five o'clock.

26:00.000 --> 26:01.000
Said Mike.

26:01.000 --> 26:02.000
It's time to go back.

26:02.000 --> 26:05.000
Dinner is at half past six.

26:05.000 --> 26:09.000
On the way back we can stop at the supermarket and buy some cold drinks.

26:09.000 --> 26:10.000
Good idea.

26:10.000 --> 26:11.000
Said Kate.

26:11.000 --> 26:13.000
We didn't have much luck today.

26:13.000 --> 26:17.000
We'll explore the area south of Bodega Bay tomorrow.

26:17.000 --> 26:19.000
Said Mike.

26:19.000 --> 26:23.000
Yeah, there are red lines that go all the way to Doran Beach.

26:23.000 --> 26:24.000
Said Carlos.

26:24.000 --> 26:26.000
Red lines probably mean something.

26:26.000 --> 26:27.000
I hope so.

26:27.000 --> 26:29.000
Said Mike.

26:29.000 --> 26:36.000
Dinner time was fun because Mrs. Sullivan cooked a great meal and everyone had something to say about the day.

26:36.000 --> 26:40.000
After dinner they all played cards and went to bed early.

26:40.000 --> 26:46.000
The next morning Mrs. Sullivan made sandwiches for Kate, Mike, and Carlos.

26:46.000 --> 26:49.000
Dad and I are going to go to Point Reyes again today.

26:49.000 --> 26:50.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

26:50.000 --> 26:52.000
Where are you going?

26:53.000 --> 26:56.000
Oh, we're going to take a long walk on the beach.

26:56.000 --> 26:57.000
Said Kate.

26:57.000 --> 27:00.000
Don't forget to put on some sun protection then.

27:00.000 --> 27:02.000
See you at dinner.

27:02.000 --> 27:03.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

27:03.000 --> 27:05.000
Have fun.

27:05.000 --> 27:11.000
Kate, Mike, and Carlos started walking south to Doran Beach and lucky ran ahead of them.

27:11.000 --> 27:17.000
It was a beautiful sunny day and there were a lot of people on the beach enjoying the sun.

27:17.000 --> 27:21.000
Behind the long beach there was a tall cliff.

27:22.000 --> 27:25.000
Suddenly Carlos saw a small opening in the cliff.

27:25.000 --> 27:27.000
Hey, look over there.

27:27.000 --> 27:28.000
He said.

27:28.000 --> 27:30.000
There's a small opening.

27:30.000 --> 27:33.000
Let's go inside and look around.

27:33.000 --> 27:34.000
Said Mike.

27:34.000 --> 27:37.000
Kate, Carlos, and Lucky slowly followed him.

27:37.000 --> 27:39.000
It's a cave.

27:39.000 --> 27:41.000
Said Carlos excitedly.

27:41.000 --> 27:43.000
Did you bring a flashlight?

27:43.000 --> 27:44.000
Yeah.

27:44.000 --> 27:45.000
Here it is.

27:45.000 --> 27:46.000
Said Mike.

27:46.000 --> 27:47.000
Turning it on.

27:48.000 --> 27:51.000
Look, there's some stone steps that go down.

27:51.000 --> 27:53.000
Perhaps they go to another cave.

27:53.000 --> 27:54.000
Said Carlos.

27:54.000 --> 27:55.000
Let's go.

27:55.000 --> 27:58.000
Is this where the treasure is, do you think?

27:58.000 --> 27:59.000
Asked Kate.

27:59.000 --> 28:01.000
It's a good hiding place.

28:01.000 --> 28:02.000
Said Mike.

28:02.000 --> 28:04.000
Walking slowly down the stone steps.

28:04.000 --> 28:05.000
Gee.

28:05.000 --> 28:08.000
It's really dark and scary in here.

28:08.000 --> 28:09.000
Said Kate.

28:09.000 --> 28:15.000
The three friends walked into another cave and there was some seawater on the ground.

28:15.000 --> 28:17.000
It's not very dark in here.

28:17.000 --> 28:19.000
Said Mike, looking up.

28:19.000 --> 28:21.000
There's a hole up there.

28:21.000 --> 28:22.000
A small opening.

28:22.000 --> 28:23.000
Said Carlos.

28:23.000 --> 28:25.000
And I can see the sky.

28:25.000 --> 28:27.000
How strange.

28:27.000 --> 28:30.000
Said Kate, who was a bit nervous.

28:30.000 --> 28:34.000
They looked around the cave, but it was empty.

28:34.000 --> 28:36.000
Then suddenly Carlos saw something.

28:36.000 --> 28:38.000
Mike, come here with your flashlight.

28:38.000 --> 28:39.000
Cried Carlos.

28:39.000 --> 28:42.000
There's something in the corner over here.

28:42.000 --> 28:44.000
Oh, let's see.

28:44.000 --> 28:47.000
Said Mike, looking in the dark corner with his flashlight.

28:47.000 --> 28:50.000
There's a big old box.

28:50.000 --> 28:52.000
Box?

28:52.000 --> 28:53.000
Cried Kate.

28:53.000 --> 28:55.000
It's the treasure chest.

28:55.000 --> 29:00.000
The three friends were surprised and looked at each other and lucky started barking.

29:00.000 --> 29:03.000
You're right.

29:03.000 --> 29:05.000
Cried Mike and Carlos.

29:05.000 --> 29:07.000
They looked at the big wooden box.

29:07.000 --> 29:09.000
It was very old.

29:09.000 --> 29:10.000
It's the treasure.

29:10.000 --> 29:12.000
Said Kate excitedly.

29:12.000 --> 29:15.000
But we don't know what's inside.

29:15.000 --> 29:16.000
Said Carlos.

29:16.000 --> 29:18.000
Well, let's open it.

29:18.000 --> 29:19.000
Said Mike.

29:19.000 --> 29:21.000
There's a big lock on it.

29:21.000 --> 29:22.000
Said Kate.

29:22.000 --> 29:24.000
Let's break the old lock.

29:24.000 --> 29:25.000
Said Mike.

29:25.000 --> 29:29.000
Mike took a big stone and hit the lock a few times.

29:29.000 --> 29:31.000
But it didn't break.

29:31.000 --> 29:32.000
Here.

29:32.000 --> 29:33.000
Said Kate.

29:33.000 --> 29:34.000
Try with this stone.

29:34.000 --> 29:36.000
It's much bigger.

29:36.000 --> 29:38.000
But the old lock didn't break.

29:38.000 --> 29:39.000
Let me try.

29:39.000 --> 29:40.000
Said Carlos.

29:40.000 --> 29:42.000
Hitting the lock again.

29:42.000 --> 29:45.000
Suddenly, the old lock broke.

29:45.000 --> 29:53.000
And they were ready to open Captain Salamanca's treasure chest.

29:53.000 --> 29:54.000
Chapter 5.

29:54.000 --> 29:57.000
Well done lucky.

29:57.000 --> 30:00.000
Who's going to open the treasure chest?

30:00.000 --> 30:02.000
Asked Carlos, looking at Mike and Kate.

30:02.000 --> 30:05.000
Mike, you took the old map.

30:05.000 --> 30:06.000
Said Kate.

30:06.000 --> 30:09.000
So, you can open the treasure chest.

30:09.000 --> 30:12.000
Mike slowly opened the old chest.

30:12.000 --> 30:16.000
Suddenly, the three friends jumped back and Kate screamed.

30:16.000 --> 30:18.000
Aaah!

30:18.000 --> 30:20.000
There was something terrible inside.

30:20.000 --> 30:21.000
A skeleton.

30:21.000 --> 30:24.000
Lucky started barking loudly.

30:24.000 --> 30:25.000
Aaah!

30:25.000 --> 30:26.000
Aaah!

30:26.000 --> 30:30.000
The skeleton was wearing pirates clothes and a big black hat.

30:30.000 --> 30:35.000
Mike, Kate, and Carlos stared at it and didn't know what to say.

30:35.000 --> 30:38.000
They were very surprised and scared.

30:38.000 --> 30:40.000
Kate spoke first.

30:40.000 --> 30:42.000
Is this the treasure?

30:42.000 --> 30:44.000
It's terrible.

30:44.000 --> 30:47.000
Maybe there's something else in the treasure chest.

30:47.000 --> 30:48.000
Said Carlos.

30:48.000 --> 30:52.000
He slowly moved closer to the chest and looked inside.

30:52.000 --> 30:55.000
There's nothing inside except the skeleton.

30:55.000 --> 30:57.000
He said sadly.

30:57.000 --> 31:03.000
Why did someone put the body of a pirate inside the treasure chest and lock it?

31:03.000 --> 31:05.000
Asked Mike.

31:05.000 --> 31:08.000
Suddenly, Lucky started barking again.

31:08.000 --> 31:09.000
Aaah!

31:09.000 --> 31:14.000
The three friends turned around and saw that water was coming down the stone steps.

31:14.000 --> 31:16.000
What's happening?

31:16.000 --> 31:17.000
Asked Kate nervously.

31:17.000 --> 31:20.000
Why is water coming in here?

31:20.000 --> 31:22.000
Oh no, the tide!

31:22.000 --> 31:23.000
Said Mike.

31:23.000 --> 31:28.000
It's high tide and these caves fill up with seawater.

31:28.000 --> 31:30.000
We have to get out of here now.

31:30.000 --> 31:31.000
But wait!

31:31.000 --> 31:32.000
Said Carlos.

31:32.000 --> 31:36.000
Perhaps there's a clue or another map in the skeleton's clothes in his pockets.

31:36.000 --> 31:39.000
Are you going to touch it?

31:39.000 --> 31:41.000
Asked Kate, who was scared.

31:41.000 --> 31:43.000
I'll just touch his clothes.

31:43.000 --> 31:44.000
Said Carlos.

31:44.000 --> 31:45.000
We have to hurry.

31:45.000 --> 31:46.000
Said Mike.

31:46.000 --> 31:50.000
If more water comes in, we'll be in big trouble.

31:50.000 --> 31:54.000
Carlos started touching the skeleton's clothes.

31:54.000 --> 31:57.000
He looked in all the pockets but found nothing.

31:57.000 --> 32:01.000
Then he took off the big black hat and looked inside it.

32:01.000 --> 32:03.000
There's something inside the hat.

32:03.000 --> 32:04.000
Cried Carlos.

32:04.000 --> 32:10.000
It's an old piece of paper that says Juan Martinez de los Robles.

32:10.000 --> 32:14.000
He took the old piece of paper and showed it to Kate and Mike.

32:14.000 --> 32:16.000
Maybe that was his name.

32:16.000 --> 32:17.000
Said Kate.

32:17.000 --> 32:19.000
No, I don't think so.

32:19.000 --> 32:20.000
Said Mike.

32:20.000 --> 32:25.000
You don't write your name on a piece of paper and put it in your hat.

32:25.000 --> 32:28.000
I think it's a clue.

32:28.000 --> 32:31.000
Carlos quickly put the piece of paper in his pocket.

32:31.000 --> 32:38.000
Lucky started barking loudly again because a lot of water was now coming into the cave.

32:38.000 --> 32:40.000
Mike picked him up.

32:40.000 --> 32:45.000
The three friends couldn't get out because water was coming down the stone steps.

32:45.000 --> 32:48.000
And the cave was quickly filling up with water.

32:48.000 --> 32:50.000
They were in big trouble.

32:50.000 --> 32:52.000
How can we get out of here?

32:52.000 --> 32:55.000
Asked Kate, who was now starting to get very scared.

32:55.000 --> 32:57.000
The water is almost up to my knees.

32:57.000 --> 32:59.000
There's only one way out.

32:59.000 --> 33:03.000
Said Mike, looking at the small hole high above their heads.

33:03.000 --> 33:05.000
But we can't climb up there.

33:05.000 --> 33:06.000
Said Carlos.

33:06.000 --> 33:07.000
It's impossible.

33:07.000 --> 33:10.000
We need someone on the outside to throw down a rope.

33:10.000 --> 33:12.000
I have an idea.

33:12.000 --> 33:13.000
Said Mike.

33:13.000 --> 33:18.000
Kate, if you hold Lucky, Carlos and I can lift you.

33:18.000 --> 33:21.000
Then you can push Lucky up to the top.

33:21.000 --> 33:25.000
He is small and light and can get out of the hole.

33:25.000 --> 33:29.000
Mike looked at Lucky, who was in his arms and said,

33:29.000 --> 33:31.000
Listen carefully, Lucky.

33:31.000 --> 33:33.000
Go and find help.

33:33.000 --> 33:37.000
Carlos and Mike lifted Kate and Lucky.

33:37.000 --> 33:43.000
It wasn't easy, but they were able to get Kate quite high and she pushed Lucky outside.

33:43.000 --> 33:46.000
There were a lot of people on the beach that day.

33:46.000 --> 33:52.000
And when Lucky got out of the hole, he started barking loudly and running around.

33:53.000 --> 33:55.000
What's that dog doing?

33:55.000 --> 33:58.000
Said a tall young man who was sitting on the beach with some friends.

33:58.000 --> 34:00.000
He's very excited.

34:00.000 --> 34:01.000
Said his friend.

34:01.000 --> 34:03.000
He's trying to tell us something.

34:03.000 --> 34:05.000
Perhaps someone needs help.

34:05.000 --> 34:07.000
Said another young man.

34:07.000 --> 34:09.000
Let's follow him and see.

34:09.000 --> 34:13.000
The four young men followed Lucky to the small hole and looked inside.

34:13.000 --> 34:15.000
Does anyone need help?

34:15.000 --> 34:17.000
Shouted the tall young man.

34:17.000 --> 34:22.000
Yes, the water in the cave is up to our knees and we can't get out.

34:22.000 --> 34:23.000
Shouted Mike.

34:23.000 --> 34:25.000
Can you please help us?

34:25.000 --> 34:27.000
It's high tide.

34:27.000 --> 34:29.000
Shouted the young man.

34:29.000 --> 34:32.000
Don't worry, we can get you out of there.

34:32.000 --> 34:34.000
I've got a rope in my car.

34:34.000 --> 34:36.000
Wait a moment and I'll be back.

34:36.000 --> 34:42.000
He ran across the beach to the parking lot, got a long rope from his car and ran back.

34:42.000 --> 34:44.000
Okay, listen.

34:44.000 --> 34:47.000
Shouted the young man who was standing over the hole.

34:47.000 --> 34:50.000
I'm going to send this rope down to you.

34:50.000 --> 34:51.000
Hold on to it.

34:51.000 --> 34:54.000
Then my friends and I will pull you up.

34:54.000 --> 34:56.000
Okay.

34:56.000 --> 34:58.000
Shouted Kate, Mike, and Carlos.

34:58.000 --> 35:04.000
The four young men pulled Kate up first, then Carlos, and then Mike.

35:04.000 --> 35:07.000
Lucky jumped into Kate's arms and looked at her.

35:07.000 --> 35:08.000
Thanks, Lucky.

35:08.000 --> 35:11.000
Said Kate, smiling at the little black dog.

35:12.000 --> 35:13.000
And thank you.

35:13.000 --> 35:16.000
She said, looking at the four young men.

35:16.000 --> 35:17.000
Yeah.

35:17.000 --> 35:18.000
Said Mike.

35:18.000 --> 35:19.000
Thanks a lot.

35:19.000 --> 35:21.000
You were very kind to help us.

35:21.000 --> 35:22.000
Said Carlos.

35:22.000 --> 35:24.000
We were in big trouble down there.

35:25.000 --> 35:28.000
You guys are lucky, said one of the men.

35:28.000 --> 35:32.000
I always keep a rope in my car because my friends and I are mountain climbers.

35:32.000 --> 35:34.000
What were you doing in the cave?

35:34.000 --> 35:36.000
Ask the tall young man.

35:36.000 --> 35:39.000
Oh, we were just looking around?

35:39.000 --> 35:42.000
Said Mike, and his face became red.

35:42.000 --> 35:44.000
Oh, well, it's getting late.

35:44.000 --> 35:45.000
Said Kate.

35:45.000 --> 35:47.000
We have to go back to Bodega Bay.

35:47.000 --> 35:49.000
Thanks again for your help.

35:49.000 --> 35:50.000
We were happy to help you.

35:50.000 --> 35:52.000
Said the tall young man.

35:52.000 --> 35:54.000
But next time, be careful.

35:54.000 --> 35:55.000
Okay.

35:55.000 --> 35:56.000
We will.

35:56.000 --> 35:58.000
Said the three friends.

36:02.000 --> 36:03.000
Pirates.

36:03.000 --> 36:08.000
A long time ago, ships were the only form of transport to cross the sea.

36:08.000 --> 36:11.000
The seas were full of pirates and they robbed ships.

36:11.000 --> 36:14.000
Sometimes they killed the crew too.

36:14.000 --> 36:17.000
Pirates were dangerous people.

36:17.000 --> 36:21.000
Their sailing ships usually had the Jolly Roger flag.

36:21.000 --> 36:24.000
Let's take a look at some pirates from the past.

36:24.000 --> 36:26.000
Blackbeard.

36:26.000 --> 36:33.000
The most famous pirate was probably Edward Teach, 1680-1718.

36:33.000 --> 36:37.000
He was called Blackbeard because he had a long time.

36:37.000 --> 36:40.000
Because he had a long Blackbeard.

36:40.000 --> 36:45.000
He always wore a lot of knives and guns because he wanted to scare people.

36:45.000 --> 36:51.000
He and his pirates robbed a lot of ships in the Caribbean Sea and in the Atlantic Ocean.

36:51.000 --> 36:57.000
Blackbeard had a very big treasure, but no one knows where he hid it.

36:57.000 --> 37:01.000
He was killed during a long battle with the British Navy.

37:01.000 --> 37:03.000
Black Bart.

37:03.000 --> 37:10.000
Bartholomew Roberts, 1682-1722, was another famous pirate.

37:10.000 --> 37:16.000
He was also called Black Bart and he was a very successful pirate.

37:16.000 --> 37:27.000
Between 1719 and 1722, he robbed more than 470 ships in the Caribbean Sea and in the Atlantic Ocean.

37:27.000 --> 37:32.000
He was an unusual pirate because he was always clean and well dressed.

37:32.000 --> 37:35.000
He liked reading books and listening to music.

37:35.000 --> 37:38.000
There were always musicians on his ships.

37:38.000 --> 37:41.000
He was killed during a battle at sea.

37:41.000 --> 37:45.000
Anne Bonnie, Mary Reed, and Calico Jack.

37:45.000 --> 37:55.000
Anne Bonnie, 1700-1782, was Irish and Mary Reed, 1690-1721, was English.

37:55.000 --> 37:59.000
They were female pirates in the early 1700s.

37:59.000 --> 38:02.000
They dressed like men and fought like men.

38:02.000 --> 38:09.000
Anne Bonnie loved another pirate, Calico Jack, 1682-1720.

38:09.000 --> 38:15.000
Anne, Mary, and Calico Jack lived together as pirates in the Caribbean Sea.

38:15.000 --> 38:19.000
Together they robbed a lot of ships and had a big treasure.

38:19.000 --> 38:27.000
In 1720, after a battle with a British ship, Anne, Mary, and Calico Jack were put in prison.

38:27.000 --> 38:31.000
Calico Jack was hanged and Mary died in prison.

38:31.000 --> 38:37.000
People think that Anne left prison and went to live in the American colonies.

38:37.000 --> 38:39.000
Pirates today.

38:39.000 --> 38:43.000
Today there are modern pirates in different parts of the world.

38:43.000 --> 38:50.000
Indonesia, the Philippines, the South China Sea, Somalia, Brazil, and the Florida coast.

38:50.000 --> 38:55.000
They are dangerous and have fast modern boats and big guns.

38:55.000 --> 38:58.000
They go on to ships and rob them.

38:58.000 --> 39:04.000
Military forces around the world and international organizations, such as the United Nations,

39:04.000 --> 39:11.000
have a difficult job trying to stop them.

39:11.000 --> 39:15.000
Chapter 6, the Hacienda Estrada.

39:15.000 --> 39:20.000
Mike, Kate, and Carlos got back to the pelican at dinner time.

39:20.000 --> 39:22.000
Hi, said Mr. Sullivan.

39:22.000 --> 39:26.000
We did a lot of interesting work today at Point Reyes.

39:26.000 --> 39:30.000
We saw two great white shark swimming by.

39:30.000 --> 39:33.000
Tomorrow we're going to the Farallon Islands.

39:33.000 --> 39:34.000
How was your day?

39:34.000 --> 39:36.000
Asked Mrs. Sullivan.

39:36.000 --> 39:38.000
Ah, interesting.

39:38.000 --> 39:41.000
Said Mike, looking at his sister and Carlos.

39:41.000 --> 39:44.000
We explored the beach, said Carlos.

39:44.000 --> 39:46.000
Are you guys getting bored?

39:46.000 --> 39:48.000
Asked Mr. Sullivan.

39:49.000 --> 39:51.000
Said Kate, smiling.

39:51.000 --> 39:53.000
No, of course not.

39:53.000 --> 39:58.000
The next morning after breakfast, Mr. and Mrs. Sullivan sailed to the Farallon Islands.

39:58.000 --> 40:05.000
It was a foggy morning and the three friends stood on the pier and talked about their scary adventure in the cave.

40:05.000 --> 40:11.000
Carlos took out the old piece of paper he found in the skeleton's hat and looked at it.

40:11.000 --> 40:13.000
Is this a clue?

40:13.000 --> 40:14.000
What does it mean?

40:14.000 --> 40:15.000
He asked.

40:15.000 --> 40:17.000
It's the name of a man.

40:17.000 --> 40:19.000
Or perhaps it isn't.

40:19.000 --> 40:20.000
Said Kate.

40:20.000 --> 40:24.000
Let's take another look at the map, said Mike.

40:24.000 --> 40:28.000
Why don't we go to the tourist office and ask about the Hacienda Astrada?

40:28.000 --> 40:29.000
Said Kate.

40:29.000 --> 40:32.000
Perhaps we can get some useful information.

40:32.000 --> 40:34.000
Okay, said Carlos.

40:34.000 --> 40:37.000
I'm sure the treasure is here somewhere.

40:37.000 --> 40:44.000
Margaret Healy worked at the Bodega Bay tourist office and knew all about the history of the town.

40:45.000 --> 40:50.000
The Astrada family was a rich and important family in the 1600s.

40:50.000 --> 40:51.000
Said Margaret.

40:51.000 --> 40:58.000
They were the first to build a home and a big farm here, the Hacienda Astrada.

40:58.000 --> 41:06.000
The family's only daughter was called Isabella and she married a sea captain called Juan Martinez.

41:06.000 --> 41:14.000
Soon after their marriage he was killed during a terrible fight with pirates and his young wife never married again.

41:14.000 --> 41:17.000
She was always sad and dressed in black.

41:17.000 --> 41:19.000
She rarely left the Hacienda.

41:19.000 --> 41:21.000
What a sad story.

41:21.000 --> 41:23.000
Said Kate.

41:23.000 --> 41:28.000
Was the captain's last name Robles or Delos Robles?

41:28.000 --> 41:30.000
asked Mike.

41:30.000 --> 41:31.000
No.

41:31.000 --> 41:32.000
answered Margaret.

41:32.000 --> 41:35.000
His last name was Martinez.

41:35.000 --> 41:37.000
Where was he buried?

41:37.000 --> 41:38.000
asked Carlos.

41:38.000 --> 41:39.000
No one knows.

41:39.000 --> 41:41.000
said Margaret.

41:41.000 --> 41:43.000
What about the old town cemetery?

41:43.000 --> 41:44.000
asked Kate.

41:44.000 --> 41:50.000
It's about 400 years old and no one can read the names on the tombstones anymore.

41:50.000 --> 41:51.000
She said.

41:51.000 --> 41:58.000
If you're looking for old Spanish things go and see the lighthouse at Twin Oaks Point.

41:58.000 --> 42:00.000
It's on the cliff.

42:00.000 --> 42:03.000
The three friends thanked her and left.

42:03.000 --> 42:09.000
They decided to follow the treasure map and go to the area northwest of Bodega Bay.

42:09.000 --> 42:13.000
They climbed up the green hills and stopped near a stone wall.

42:13.000 --> 42:15.000
What's this?

42:15.000 --> 42:17.000
asked Mike looking at the map.

42:17.000 --> 42:20.000
It looks like part of the old Hacienda Estrada.

42:20.000 --> 42:21.000
said Carlos.

42:21.000 --> 42:24.000
Look there's a small river nearby too.

42:24.000 --> 42:26.000
The same river that's on the map.

42:26.000 --> 42:31.000
They looked around and saw another stone wall and some steps.

42:31.000 --> 42:33.000
This looks like a wall of a house.

42:33.000 --> 42:35.000
Maybe the Hacienda.

42:35.000 --> 42:36.000
said Kate.

42:37.000 --> 42:40.000
Yeah, but there's almost nothing here.

42:40.000 --> 42:41.000
said Mike.

42:41.000 --> 42:45.000
Let's move on and see if we can find the cemetery.

42:45.000 --> 42:49.000
They walked to the cliff and a strong wind was blowing.

42:49.000 --> 42:52.000
From the top of the cliff they could see the Pacific Ocean.

42:52.000 --> 42:54.000
What a beautiful place.

42:54.000 --> 42:57.000
said Kate, looking at the green blue sea.

42:57.000 --> 42:59.000
Let's stop here and have lunch.

42:59.000 --> 43:00.000
I'm hungry.

43:00.000 --> 43:01.000
We are too.

43:01.000 --> 43:03.000
said Mike and Carlos.

43:03.000 --> 43:07.000
They sat down and had chicken sandwiches and fruit juice.

43:07.000 --> 43:10.000
Hey, look down there.

43:10.000 --> 43:12.000
said Carlos eating his sandwich.

43:12.000 --> 43:20.000
From the top of the cliff they saw the old cemetery that was on Salamanca's map and the old Spanish lighthouse.

43:20.000 --> 43:25.000
After lunch they slowly climbed down and got to the old cemetery.

43:25.000 --> 43:27.000
There isn't much here.

43:27.000 --> 43:28.000
said Mike.

43:28.000 --> 43:32.000
Just a few very old tombstones and lots of grass.

43:32.000 --> 43:34.000
Gee, look at this one.

43:34.000 --> 43:35.000
said Kate.

43:35.000 --> 43:40.000
I can't read the name, but the date is 1624.

43:40.000 --> 43:43.000
This place is probably full of ghosts.

43:43.000 --> 43:44.000
Let's go.

43:44.000 --> 43:45.000
I'm scared.

43:45.000 --> 43:47.000
Carlos laughed and said.

43:47.000 --> 43:50.000
We'll never find the treasure here.

43:50.000 --> 43:52.000
Perhaps there isn't any treasure.

43:52.000 --> 43:53.000
said Kate.

43:53.000 --> 43:55.000
I'm sure there's a treasure.

43:55.000 --> 43:56.000
said Mike.

43:56.000 --> 44:00.000
Don't forget that Captain Salamanca was looking for it.

44:00.000 --> 44:02.000
And we have his map.

44:02.000 --> 44:03.000
You're right, Mike.

44:03.000 --> 44:04.000
said Carlos.

44:04.000 --> 44:07.000
We have to study the clues carefully.

44:07.000 --> 44:12.000
The name Juan Martinez de los Robles means something.

44:12.000 --> 44:14.000
But what?

44:14.000 --> 44:16.000
We have to find out.

44:20.000 --> 44:22.000
Listening activity.

44:23.000 --> 44:26.000
Good morning. How can I help you?

44:26.000 --> 44:28.000
A good morning.

44:28.000 --> 44:32.000
My friends and I are looking for Hacienda Estrada.

44:32.000 --> 44:34.000
What's the best way to get there?

44:34.000 --> 44:37.000
Well, there are two ways to get there.

44:37.000 --> 44:42.000
You can follow the small road on the right side of the supermarket parking lot.

44:42.000 --> 44:46.000
And when you get to a big tree, turn right.

44:46.000 --> 44:51.000
And keep walking until you see the old stone water well.

44:51.000 --> 44:52.000
And turn left.

44:52.000 --> 44:54.000
It's the fastest road.

44:54.000 --> 44:57.000
How long will it take us to get there?

44:57.000 --> 45:02.000
Well, it'll take you about two hours if the weather is good.

45:02.000 --> 45:08.000
But remember to wear good climbing shoes because the road is in bad condition.

45:08.000 --> 45:09.000
It's dangerous.

45:09.000 --> 45:12.000
And remember to bring some water too.

45:12.000 --> 45:14.000
Climbing can make you thirsty.

45:14.000 --> 45:20.000
The last time I went there I had to bring a hat and an umbrella because it was raining.

45:21.000 --> 45:26.000
We want to go to Tomales Bay to see the show at the Tomales Bay Museum.

45:26.000 --> 45:28.000
How can we get there?

45:28.000 --> 45:32.000
There are three shows in Tomales Bay this summer.

45:32.000 --> 45:35.000
One is on sharks in the Pacific Ocean.

45:35.000 --> 45:37.000
The other is on pirate ships.

45:37.000 --> 45:40.000
And still another is on seabirds.

45:40.000 --> 45:42.000
Which one do you want to see?

45:42.000 --> 45:46.000
We're really interested in pirate ships and in sharks.

45:46.000 --> 45:52.000
The show on pirate ships opens at 10 in the morning and closes after lunch.

45:52.000 --> 45:56.000
And the one on sharks opens at 2 in the afternoon.

45:56.000 --> 46:02.000
If you catch the ferry boat today at half past 11 you can see the show on sharks.

46:02.000 --> 46:09.000
But if you want to see the one on pirate ships then you have to catch the early morning ferry at half past 8.

46:09.000 --> 46:13.000
Where can we catch the ferry boat for Tomales Bay?

46:13.000 --> 46:19.000
On weekdays the ferry boat leaves from pier number 3 at half past 8.

46:19.000 --> 46:22.000
And from pier number 5 at half past 11.

46:22.000 --> 46:26.000
You can buy tickets from the ferry boat office on the pier.

46:26.000 --> 46:34.000
On weekends though all ferry boats for Tomales Bay leave from pier number 1 at the same times.

46:34.000 --> 46:37.000
And you must buy tickets on the boat.

46:37.000 --> 46:40.000
How much are ferry boat tickets to Tomales Bay?

46:40.000 --> 46:48.000
On weekdays round trip tickets cost $15 each and on weekends they cost $18.

46:48.000 --> 46:50.000
Can we buy lunch on the ferry?

46:50.000 --> 46:58.000
Yes you can. There's a special meal deal that costs $8 and you get a big hamburger, fries and a drink.

46:58.000 --> 47:02.000
Or you can spend only $6 and get a smaller lunch.

47:02.000 --> 47:05.000
A cheese sandwich, an apple and a drink.

47:05.000 --> 47:11.000
And if you add just $1 to the price of the special ticket you get a bag of cookies.

47:11.000 --> 47:14.000
Well that sounds great. Thank you.

47:17.000 --> 47:21.000
Chapter 7 The Old Lighthouse

47:21.000 --> 47:25.000
Let's go and see the old lighthouse at Twin Oaks Point.

47:25.000 --> 47:26.000
Said Carlos.

47:26.000 --> 47:28.000
Lighthouses are always interesting.

47:28.000 --> 47:34.000
It was a windy day and they walked along the cliff for almost an hour to get there.

47:34.000 --> 47:39.000
There was an old stone lighthouse on the cliff above the sea near two big oak trees.

47:39.000 --> 47:44.000
This was probably an important lighthouse in Captain Salamanca's days.

47:44.000 --> 47:45.000
Said Mike.

47:45.000 --> 47:49.000
Those two big oak trees look very old too.

47:49.000 --> 47:52.000
That's why people called it Twin Oaks Point.

47:52.000 --> 47:54.000
Said Kate laughing.

47:54.000 --> 47:58.000
Carlos suddenly turned around and looked at the two oak trees.

47:59.000 --> 48:01.000
Wait a minute, he said.

48:01.000 --> 48:04.000
The Spanish word for oak is Roble.

48:04.000 --> 48:10.000
And the words De los Robles are written next to Juan Martinez's name.

48:10.000 --> 48:12.000
That means of the oaks.

48:12.000 --> 48:16.000
Perhaps Robles isn't part of his last name but a clue.

48:16.000 --> 48:18.000
Oh you're right Carlos.

48:18.000 --> 48:19.000
Said Mike.

48:19.000 --> 48:22.000
Robles could be a clue.

48:22.000 --> 48:25.000
Perhaps he is buried under the oak trees.

48:25.000 --> 48:27.000
There are only two oaks in this area.

48:27.000 --> 48:30.000
Said Kate, looking at the two big trees.

48:30.000 --> 48:34.000
The three friends ran to the oak trees and looked around.

48:34.000 --> 48:37.000
There was a lot of tall grass under them.

48:37.000 --> 48:39.000
Suddenly Mike said.

48:39.000 --> 48:43.000
Look, under the grass there's a small tombstone.

48:43.000 --> 48:45.000
And half of it is underground.

48:45.000 --> 48:48.000
Let's try and pull it out.

48:48.000 --> 48:52.000
They slowly pulled it out and looked at the name on the tombstone.

48:53.000 --> 49:00.000
Well it's difficult to read but I think it says Juan Martinez.

49:00.000 --> 49:04.000
1570 to 1605.

49:04.000 --> 49:05.000
Said Mike.

49:05.000 --> 49:09.000
It's the name of the sea captain the pirates killed.

49:09.000 --> 49:10.000
Said Carlos excitedly.

49:10.000 --> 49:13.000
He was Isabella Estrada's husband.

49:13.000 --> 49:17.000
Could Captain Salamanca's treasure be here?

49:17.000 --> 49:19.000
What do you mean?

49:20.000 --> 49:23.000
This is where Juan Martinez is buried.

49:23.000 --> 49:25.000
Yes, cried Carlos.

49:25.000 --> 49:28.000
It's the perfect hiding place.

49:28.000 --> 49:30.000
There's only one way to find out.

49:30.000 --> 49:31.000
Said Mike.

49:31.000 --> 49:33.000
We have to dig.

49:33.000 --> 49:35.000
Aren't you afraid?

49:35.000 --> 49:36.000
Asked Kate.

49:36.000 --> 49:38.000
Isn't it bad luck?

49:38.000 --> 49:41.000
I just want to dig under the tombstone.

49:41.000 --> 49:42.000
Said Mike.

49:42.000 --> 49:45.000
But we don't have a spade.

49:45.000 --> 49:47.000
Said Carlos.

49:47.000 --> 49:51.000
Three friends were silent for a moment.

49:51.000 --> 49:52.000
You know.

49:52.000 --> 49:53.000
Said Kate.

49:53.000 --> 49:56.000
Dad has two spades on the boat.

49:56.000 --> 49:59.000
He uses them for his work.

49:59.000 --> 50:02.000
That means we have to tell mom and dad.

50:02.000 --> 50:03.000
Said Mike.

50:03.000 --> 50:05.000
I think so.

50:05.000 --> 50:06.000
Said Kate.

50:06.000 --> 50:08.000
I'm sure they'll help us.

50:08.000 --> 50:10.000
They always do.

50:10.000 --> 50:13.000
We can tell them at dinner.

50:14.000 --> 50:19.000
Kate, Mike and Carlos told Mr. and Mrs. Sullivan the whole story.

50:19.000 --> 50:22.000
They stopped dating and were very surprised.

50:22.000 --> 50:24.000
But they were not angry.

50:24.000 --> 50:27.000
They decided to help the three friends.

50:27.000 --> 50:30.000
This is an exciting adventure.

50:30.000 --> 50:32.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

50:32.000 --> 50:34.000
And you guys are very good detectives.

50:34.000 --> 50:36.000
We'll help you.

50:36.000 --> 50:41.000
If you find the treasure, we'll have to call the California Archaeological Society.

50:41.000 --> 50:43.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

50:43.000 --> 50:47.000
Because the treasure belongs to the state of California.

50:47.000 --> 50:53.000
Tomorrow morning, we'll go to the old Spanish lighthouse and start digging.

50:53.000 --> 50:56.000
Who knows what we'll find.

50:56.000 --> 51:00.000
By ten o'clock the next morning, they were at the old Spanish lighthouse.

51:00.000 --> 51:05.000
Mr. Sullivan gave Mike and Carlos two spades and they started digging.

51:05.000 --> 51:07.000
They dug for a short time.

51:08.000 --> 51:11.000
And suddenly Carlos's spade hit something hard.

51:11.000 --> 51:14.000
He stopped digging and looked at Mike.

51:14.000 --> 51:15.000
I found something.

51:15.000 --> 51:16.000
Cried Carlos.

51:16.000 --> 51:18.000
Let me help you.

51:18.000 --> 51:20.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

51:20.000 --> 51:23.000
They pulled a small wooden treasure chest out of the ground.

51:23.000 --> 51:25.000
It was heavy.

51:25.000 --> 51:27.000
Wow.

51:27.000 --> 51:29.000
Said Kate and Mrs. Sullivan looking at it.

51:29.000 --> 51:31.000
This is hard to believe.

51:31.000 --> 51:33.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

51:33.000 --> 51:34.000
Can we open it?

51:34.000 --> 51:35.000
Asked Mike.

51:35.000 --> 51:36.000
Yes, of course.

51:36.000 --> 51:37.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

51:37.000 --> 51:39.000
Let's see what's inside.

51:39.000 --> 51:45.000
The lock was broken and Carlos and Mike slowly opened the treasure chest.

51:45.000 --> 51:52.000
It was full of gold and silver coins, jewelry, pearls and a king's crown.

51:52.000 --> 51:54.000
Wow.

51:54.000 --> 51:56.000
They all cried.

51:56.000 --> 51:58.000
They couldn't believe their eyes.

51:58.000 --> 52:01.000
Look at all of these gold and silver coins.

52:01.000 --> 52:03.000
Cried Kate.

52:04.000 --> 52:07.000
Everyone stared at the treasure in silence.

52:07.000 --> 52:09.000
But no one touched it.

52:09.000 --> 52:14.000
A pirate probably hid this treasure here in the 1600s.

52:14.000 --> 52:15.000
Said Carlos.

52:15.000 --> 52:19.000
Another pirate knew about it and planned to come here and dig up the treasure.

52:19.000 --> 52:22.000
Yeah, said Mike.

52:22.000 --> 52:26.000
And someone killed him because he didn't want to tell his secret.

52:26.000 --> 52:30.000
But he wrote his secret on a piece of paper and put it in his hat.

52:30.000 --> 52:31.000
Said Kate.

52:32.000 --> 52:35.000
And we found it after 400 years.

52:35.000 --> 52:38.000
Why did Captain Salamanca have the treasure map?

52:38.000 --> 52:39.000
Asked Carlos.

52:39.000 --> 52:41.000
That's a mystery.

52:41.000 --> 52:43.000
Said Mike smiling.

52:43.000 --> 52:45.000
What an exciting story.

52:45.000 --> 52:47.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

52:47.000 --> 52:50.000
Captain Salamanca's treasure map brought you good luck.

52:50.000 --> 52:54.000
People don't find treasures every day in California.

52:54.000 --> 52:56.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

52:56.000 --> 53:00.000
Now, I'm going to call the California Archaeological Society in San Francisco.

53:00.000 --> 53:04.000
They'll be very surprised and happy.

53:04.000 --> 53:06.000
What's going to happen to the treasure?

53:06.000 --> 53:08.000
Asked Mike.

53:08.000 --> 53:11.000
Archaeologists will study the treasure first.

53:11.000 --> 53:13.000
Said Mr. Sullivan.

53:13.000 --> 53:17.000
And then they'll probably take it to one of the Californian museums.

53:17.000 --> 53:20.000
Journalists may want to write about you in the newspaper.

53:20.000 --> 53:22.000
Are names in the newspaper?

53:22.000 --> 53:24.000
Said Kate, happily.

53:24.000 --> 53:25.000
That's exciting.

53:25.000 --> 53:27.000
Of course.

53:27.000 --> 53:28.000
Said Mrs. Sullivan.

53:28.000 --> 53:33.000
Your adventure will be in all the papers and maybe on TV.

53:33.000 --> 53:35.000
We're proud of you.

53:35.000 --> 53:37.000
Said Mr. Sullivan smiling.

53:37.000 --> 53:39.000
And of you too, Lucky.

53:39.000 --> 53:41.000
Lucky barked happily.

53:41.000 --> 53:46.000
And ran around the treasure chest.

53:46.000 --> 53:48.000
Everyone laughed.

53:48.000 --> 53:50.000
And Mrs. Sullivan said.

53:50.000 --> 53:54.000
Well, you didn't get bored on this vacation.

53:54.000 --> 53:55.000
Bored?

53:55.000 --> 53:57.000
The three friends said.

53:57.000 --> 53:58.000
Never.

